    <div class="card" id="CharacterCreation">
        <div>
            <h2>Character Creation</h2>

            <p>
                Character creation might seem complicated at first glance, but once you've gone through it once, every subsequent character will be easy! 
                The game runner should run through this process at least once before the group gets together to play to ensure it goes smoothly. Players should consider
                making a diverse group of characters without too much overlapping aptitudes, so they can more effectively tackle a wide array of challenges.
            </p>
            

            The character creation process goes as follows, with each step being further detailed below;
            
            <ol>
                <li>Picking a <em>Race</em></li>
                <li>Generating <em>Attribute Scores</em></li>
                <li>Choosing an <em>Identity</em></li>
                <li>Spending <em>Skill Points</em></li>
                <li>Selecting Character <em>Features</em></li>
                <li>Generating <em>Starting Wealth</em></li>
            </ol>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    
    <div class="card" id="PickRace">
        <h2>Picking a Race</h2>

        <p>
            A large part of character creation in Illusion is selecting your character’s race, as it provides an influence on your character’s attribute 
            scores and their roleplaying direction. While there are only six races present in Illusion, as shown in the table below, players are invited to 
            create their own races, or modify the existing ones, so long as the other players at the table, specifically the Game Master, are okay with it. 
            Each character is required to have one race attributed to their character, no more, no less.
        </p>

        <p>
            Presented below are the mechanical effects of each race, but those interested in more details regarding each race's personality and fixture in the 
            World of Illusion can refer to the <a href="/Illusion Lite Pages/Races">Races section under the core rules.</a>
        </p>
        
        <table id="FullTable">
            <tr>
                <th>Race</th> <th>Bonus</th> <th>Penalty</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Dwarf</td>
                <td>Can distribute 2 points between Vigor and Reason</td>
                <td>Starting Control is reduced by 1</td>
            </tr>            
            <tr>
                <td>Elf</td>
                <td>Can distribute 2 points between Control and Logic</td>
                <td>Starting Vigor is reduced by 1</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Half-Elf</td>
                <td>Starting Disposition is improved by 1, and any one attribute is improved by 1</td>
                <td>Reduce any one attribute by 1 point</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Halfling</td>
                <td>Can distribute 2 points between Control and Disposition</td>
                <td>Starting Might is reduced by 1</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Half-Orc</td>
                <td>Can distribute 2 points among all attributes</td>
                <td>Starting Disposition is reduced by 1</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Human</td>
                <td>Improve any one attribute by 1 point</td>
                <td><em>None</em></td>
            </tr>
        </table>

        <p>
            Players might also take this time to flesh out the core concept of their character's personality. What motivates them? What do they do for a living? What are they good and bad at?
            There's plenty of ways one can make their character more than just a list of numbers and tags. Discuss with the other players who the character's are and why they're adventuring together!
        </p>
    </div>


    <div class="card" id="GenerateAttributes">
        <div>
            <div>
                <h2>Generating Attribute Scores</h2>

                <p>
                    Once everyone has their character idea decided on, all the players will next decide on their attribute scores. There are 6 primary attributes
                    in Illusion: Might, Control, Vigor, Logic, Reason, and Disposition. These are detailed in the [section on attributes]. These attributes are fairly typical for
                    table top games, and likely mean exactly what one first thinks upon reading them. The primary attributes scores are intended to be generated randomly as detailed 
                    below. Players must generate 6 numbers and then either apply them to the attributes in the order they were generated, or choose which attribute to apply each score to.
                </p>

                <h3>Generation</h3>
                <p>
                    During score generation and before applying racial bonuses, each attribute score can range from 2 to 5. Should a score be raised
                    over 5, or lowered below 2, the overflow is ignored and the score is set to the closest value within the accepted range, either 5 or 2. Because of this, there are
                    2 reccomended ways to generate these numbers; Roll 6, 4-sided dice (d4) and add 1 to each result, <strong>or</strong> roll 6, 6-sided dice (d6) and reroll all results 
                    of 1 or 6. Both of these methods have the same odds for each result and it really comes down to what your group prefers to roll between d4s and d6s. Write down the 
                    resulting number sets on some scratch paper and move on to applying the scores.
                </p>

                <div class="subCard">
                    <h3><em>Optional</em></h3>
                    <p>
                        Some players find random stat generation to be unfair and prefer to use "stat arrays" so that every player character at the table is on equal footing. That's just fine,
                        though it can dilude some other character mechanics. The array used should fall into the same range as rolled scores- I would recommend using the array 
                        <strong>[2, 3, 3, 4, 4, 5]</strong>, though players are welcome to come up with their own. Simply ignore the generation step and pretend these were the scores generated for each player, and apply them.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <h3>Application</h3>
                <p>
                    Once the 6 numbers are generated, they're distributed among the attributes, one to one. Once all the scores are distributed, racial bonuses are applied, which can result
                    in scores totaling over 5 or under 2, which is acceptable at this step in the process.
                </p>
                
                <h3>Determining Secondary Attributes</h3>
                <p>
                    Secondary attributes are scores that are derived from the primary attributes generated above. The meaning and application of these scores are detailed in the [section on
                    attributes], but to determine what their actual values are, refer to the outline below;


                    <table id="SecondaryAttributes">
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Resistance:</strong></td> <td>10 + Might Score + Vigor Score</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Evasion:</strong></td> <td>10 + Control Score + Logic Score</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Resolve:</strong></td> <td>10 + Disposition Score + Reason Score</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Awareness:</strong></td> <td>10 + Reason Score</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Development:</strong></td> <td>All attribute scores summed</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Destiny:</strong></td> <td>[Not yet determined]</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Health:</strong></td> <td>2 + Might Score + Vigor Score</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Movement:</strong></td> <td>1 + Control Score</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Carry Limit:</strong></td> <td>((Might &times; 2) + Vigor)</td>
                        </tr>                        
                    </table>

                    <br />
                    Once players are done determining their secondary attributes, they will be ready to move on to the next step of character creation. 
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>


