    <div class="card" id="PickingFeatures">
        <h2>Picking Features</h2>
    
        <p>
            Features are special bonuses or abilities that your character can access by selecting them during character creation or while leveling up. 
            These can be special moves to perform in combat, different ways to use a character’s existing skills, improvements to a character’s attribute 
            scores, and more. Features add a lot of character to the game and are, in a lot of ways, the heart of Illusion!
        </p>
        <p>
            Players might find that their options for what they can do during the game seem limited, but features are ultimately geared toward allowing players to
            tweak their character to play how they think it should.
        </p>
        <p>
            For example: Characters are not able to move and attack in the same action by default, but the Charge Attack enables that particular behavior if selected.
            As a result, some players might think that taking Charge Attack is a given, <em>however</em> if a player wanted their character to be a strategist, issuing
            attack orders to allies rather than ever attacking on their own, that feature point would certainly be more well spend elsewhere (might I suggest Tactician?).
        </p>
        <p>
            Not all, but some features will have one or more prerequisite before your character can take it. Prerequisites are simple requirements that must be met before
            the feature can be taken onto your character. These come in 3 forms;
        </p>   

        <ul>
            <li><strong>Score Gate:</strong> These require that certain attribute or skill score minimums are met</li>
            <li><strong>Feature Branch:</strong> These require that other features have been picked beforehand</li>
            <li><strong>Core:</strong> Core features can only be taken during character creation</li>
        </ul>

