        <div class="subCard">
            <h3><em>A Note on Bonuses</em></h3>
            <p>In case it isn't clear, a Bonus and a skill improvement are different! I'll explain;</p>
            <p>
                <strong>A skill improvement</strong> does quite exactly what it sounds like- it improves your character's score for a specific skill. A consistent rule for that, however, is that
                the score for that skill can <em>never exceed the skill's governing attribute.</em> This means, for example, if a character with a Might score of 3 and a Athletics score of 2 gains,
                for whatever reason, a skill improvement of 2 to their Athletics skill, their Athletics score will be raised to 3 and the overflow point of 1 will be lost. This is because the
                character's Athletics score can't exceed its governing attribute score, Might.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>A Bonus</strong>, is fundamentally different because there is no upper limit to a skill's bonus score. Bonuses function exactly like skill improvements during the course of
                play, but this difference is important during bookkeeping, since it can allow your character to achieve more than they might be able to normally!
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card" id="GeneratingWealth">
        <h2>Wealth</h2>
        <p>
            Coins are the most common form of currency, next to people trading goods for services and vice versa. 
            Coins scale up through 3 levels; Copper, Silver and Gold. Each coin type is worth 10 of the type below it, 
            meaning a single Gold Piece is worth 10 Silver Pieces, and a single Silver Piece is worth 10 Copper Pieces.
        </p>
        <p>
            Coins are valued for their materials and for their volume. This is mentioned because some coins can be more 
            dense, and as a result are worth more than others. Dwarf coins, for example, contain more of each material 
            than others, and are valued accordingly. Because of this, businesses will have scales and weights to determine 
            the weight of each coin before accepting it, which introduces an interesting quark; the mint of a coin doesn’t 
            matter at all, simply the material and the weight, meaning “foreign” currency is accepted all the same as chunks of raw material. 
        </p>

        <h2>Generating Starting Wealth</h2>
        <p>
            <strong>Players start with 10 + 1d8 Gold Pieces</strong>. Under normal circumstances, this is used to purchase starting equipment, but ask your 
            gamemaster in case they have other plans. This is also, setting dependant, considered a sizable amount of money, so try not to 
            be too underwhelmed when you’re party’s first treasure haul comes up not too dissimilar from what you started with! 
        </p>

    </div>
